				<text>11.7.2b first imp derivative</text>
		</name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p class="HELM_exercise">Exercise</p>
<p>Compute the derivative, \(\dfrac{dy}{dx}\) given \({@n@}x^{@a@}+y={@c@} + y^{@b@}.\)</p><p>\( \dfrac{dy}{dx} = \) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]]</p>]]></text>
		</questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p>We are given the expression \({@n@}x^{@a@}+y={@c@} + y^{@b@}.\)</p>
<p>We can deal with each term separately:<br></p>
<p>\(\dfrac{d}{dx} {@n@}x^{@a@} = {@n*a@}x^{@a-1@}.\)</p>
<p>\(\dfrac{d}{dx}y = \dfrac{dy}{dx}.\)</p>
<p>\(\dfrac{d}{dx}{@c@} = 0.\)</p>
<p>\(\dfrac{d}{dx}y^{@b@} = {@b@}y^{@b-1@} \dfrac{dy}{dx}.\)</p>
<p>This gives the equation \({@a*n@}x^{@a-1@} + \dfrac{dy}{dx}= {@b@}y^{@b-1@}\dfrac{dy}{dx}.\)</p>
<p>By rearranging, and factoring out the term \( \dfrac{dy}{dx} \), we find that \( \dfrac{dy}{dx} = \displaystyle{{@ta1@}}.\)</p>]]></text>
		</generalfeedback>
